replyContent: Hi Michael, legally, there were no satellite images of Canada in Locus ever. As Locus is not built upon Google API, it is independent, Google forbids us to use their aerial maps in our portfolio. However, there had been a third party addon enabling Google Maps in Locus but it was removed from Google Play for the terms breach. Michal, Locus team

Years of recorded tracks and data just disappeared. I restarted my phone, opened the app, and it said the working directory changed (it didn't). I selected the default directory and now all my data is gone. I tried changing to other options and restarting. Nope. All gone. This is the dumbest assumption an app could make. If data exists, why not auto import it? Why not search other common locations? Why nuke everything on startup? Even all my automated backups are gone. Which is kind boggling.
replyContent: Hi, Locus Map creates a new working directory when it can't find the original one (e.g. the original directory was on SD card that is damaged). Did you have Locus Map directory on the external SD card? If yes (and the card is not damaged), then your data is probably there. For help, please contact us at https://help.locusmap.eu/ticket/add

Updating: not simple to set up but awesome once it works. Definitely kept us going in the right direction on some poorly-maintained wilderness trails. Very deep program - I have a lot to learn to see what else it does. But, once you get past the un-intuitive setup, it's great, rock-solid, feature-rich and easy to use. I spent a good three hours figuring out how to set it up, and would have failed if my friend hadn't helped. It's not THAT hard but you have to download the map you want, then navigate to it on your phone with the app, then enable it in view, which is pretty dense. It would be nice if when you downloaded it, you have the option of "Use This Map?" But, the ability to set pins, use different folders for pins, attach files & photos to the pins, and record your track is pretty solid. It's a deep program, and if you're going to rely on it in the wilderness, sped however long it takes at home to really dial it in and understand it. I still have a lot of learning to do. But, it kept us from taking the wrong trail a dozen times on this past trip, when you're confronted with multiple animal traces, and one is your trail, this app is helpful.

content: As a tourist I like its offline navigation option, free maps (not all of course are free) and huge amount of navigation functions! one point would be great to add is the possibility to create a track on home computer (in Google maps, Yandex maps etc.) and upliad it into this application on my mobile with off-line use possibility. For example: before my trip I create on my home pc my new track on Locus web site under my accoint, then I sync it with my mobile automatically.

It works in city, but not in the mountains. Do not risk the life in wildness using this app. Two of us paid for and brought it to yosemite last weekend backpacking, but the location and tracking problems here and there. Glad someone brought other hiking app, which worked seamlessly...
replyContent: Hi, this behavior was most probably caused by your device battery optimization. Exclude Locus from it or turn it off. All information and tips on how to deal with these issues are summarized here: http://docs.locusmap.eu/doku.php?id=manual:faq:gps_lost_fix_android6 or here: https://dontkillmyapp.com/. Michal, Locus team

content: Hey, hey, hey! This app rocks! Though it took me a while to get grip on all of its functions. Originally I got it because of its offline map functionality (first because of wonky mobile network availability in the alps, second because of general battery issues during long hikes). It perfectly meets my needs. Then, with time, I learned to handle the wealth of app customisations, settings and functions. Wow! I love Locus Pro! I'm using it frequently abroad, hiking and exploring cities.

Extremely pleased! I've uninstalled all my other map apps. The one time purchase pro version is worth it, and the free one offers incredible functionality. it'd be amazing if it could link with Fatmap or Relieve to visualize tracks on fly by!
Love this app when traveling. It is great.
TIP: The map details window (i) might also display a mapsforge map file version (3,4,5) !
This is an excellent app. Its widget is worth putting on your home screen,as it allows you to track a walk without opening the app. I've tried many mapping apps, and settled on this.
One of the best outdoor navigation applications out there. There is some learning curve, but once getting used to- it's awesome.
replyContent: Good day Javier, it is not just about license, it is also a downloading of necessary libraries optimised for your device. This should anyway happen only once after installation, no more later! And for offline navigation, check for Brouter app. It's fully integrated into Locus and will be even better in next version.

content: Superb, but shame lack of UK maps. Discovered this when mountaineering in Slovenia last year and it was great then. I rarely buy the paid versions, but the Pro version really does have great and helpful extras, so I'm glad I did. Keep up the great work, developers! (But please get more UK detailed mapping!)

Hi Richard,
 for UK, we offer detailed Ordnance Survey maps, LoMaps, Freytag-Berdt maps, maps by John Thorn and of course many OSM-sourced online maps. See Locus Store. Michal, Locus team

content: I only use this app for drawing routes for hiking. It is fantastic. Beats by far the mapping function in AllTrails (which costs 20x more !). Or create your own dashboard, such as an almost entirely black (battery saving) bike computer set up. I could go on. Truly an extraordinary app.

Very easy to see when your drifting off route. This is an excellent app which won't kill your battery. August 2018. I have used Locus map pro now for five months and it is the best navigation app for your cycling. I have downloaded to a Lenovo P2 with a long battery life and I am getting two days use before the battery dies. Every feature works well, especially route tracking. Brouter works better than the Garmin 600 I used to have at navigating from your position. If you have difficulties with this app it is probably something you are doing wrong. Once you figure it all out the app cannot be bettered by any other out there. Excellent! I have now been using this app for 18 months and have found it invaluable for hiking. After plotting a route across country, many footpaths have been ploughed over, but by matching the GPS positioning to the plotted track it is possible to navigate to a stile over a mile away that you cannot even see. A simply stunning application that enables eerily accurate navigation in the UK and Europe.

With the recent update the app doesn't start when refusing to allow data sharing for GDPR. This is wrong as offline maps don't have a technical reason for data sharing. The reply by Asamm Software, s. r. o. is not accurate: the GDPR allows the user to opt out of data collection that is not essential and still use the application. I use Locus pro with offline maps so there is no need for the app to collect any data. As it stands I still can't use an application I paid for.
replyContent: Good day, there seems to be a miss-understanding. It is important to make difference between "App collects data" and "we (our servers etc.) collects data". Except for Live Tracking and Locus Store (app directly communicate with our server), all data remains in the app! There is nothing like "collecting" on our side. Contact us in case of questions.

content:
I have to say I am fairly disappointed. The app does not use the cycling 
speed sensor to calculate the distance, and therefore computes it from the 
gps trackpoints, which results in inaccurate data. The gradient is computed 
strangely (community already complained in their forums, no fix yet), which 
makes it basically unusable. Also, the pause functionality is not working 
on short stops, the timer pauses correctly when I stop, but just jumps back 
to the total time after continuing the ride. So in summary, this is nothing 
for cyclists who want to replace a dedicated cycling computer with it yet, 
but I hope future updates will solve these problems. Update: After using 
the app a bit more, I have to say it is reeeeeally good when not factoring 
in the issues mentioned above. Such a shame that this otherwise great app 
has these issues which are easily fixable.

I do not write many reviews, but I have to write one for Locus Map Pro...  This app is just extraordinary!  I have used many, many GPS apps for my adventures (Gaia, Offlinemaps+, etc.) and this one takes the cake for the features I require minus gimmicks and bugs.    From a user and software developer's standpoint, this app is a dream to use.  It allows hassle free importing of points, fully supporting KMZ rich data (CDATA picture link and icon support).  It also scales huge data sources very well.  I have over 10000 points on the map and it doesnt slow down one bit.  It's advanced features work seamlessly.  In fact, I found this app because I needed POI Proximity warning capability.  There really wasn't any other eligible app with enough features that had POI proximity alert, so I was thoroughly pleased on discovering that it works very accurately and was highly configurable.  The support for my previous navigation app I had used stopped listening to their customer base a while past (CDATA and Icon KMZ import support & POI Proximity Alert feature)...so I am happy that this app has everything I need right out-of-box.    The routing engines for navigation leave something to be desired; however this is understandable, for driving, I don't think anyone can beat Google with their realtime traffic data and routing - so I just use my Google maps for that.    This is already a 5+ star app, but for my usage, the following wish list / feedback would improve the app further:  - Larger selection of maps with downloadable areas (Openstreetmaps and Bing Maps) like Offlinemaps+, supports - especially satellite imaging, as worldwide satellite imaging is not available via Locus.  - Temporary access or cache of Google Maps/Terrain/Satellite, even if downloading areas is disabled due to TOS.  Great app guys, to support the above needs for my usage, I will continue to use Offlinemaps+ for satellite support, but the amazing features here have made this my primary adventure/travel nav app.

content: Works fine, importing GPX files on the go is very useful. Also doesn't consume much battery while navigating.

Long-time user. From my experience, this app is well worth paying for. Has been steadily adding functionality for years based on user requests and developer desires. I primarily use this for running and biking, but have also used it for hiking and driving.   Pros: - Worldwide maps for roads and trails - Multiple available maps for Europe and North America - Map overlays - Waypoints & waypoint alarms - Offline maps - Geo tagging - Stats tracking - Path filtering for improved navigation - Not a battery hog - Responsive developers - Free trial version  Cons: - Map download limits - but there's plenty of availability for reasonable use. (Not sure about the review looking for tons of USGS tiles - are you planning on hitting the entire US using only offline maps?) And you can pay for more if you need it.  - Some updates have caused temporary stability issues under certain heavy use conditions. These issues are typically resolved within a day of release, and in more than 4 years of essentially daily use spanning 4-5 phones the app has only crashed on me 2 or 3 times. - Location search is limited.

Initially, it was the only app that could record a GPS signal with my Samsung phone set in airplane mode, important to track all day without recharging. Impressive. And the choice of offline maps is mind boggling..... But.......... This app is SO complicated, the UI so chock full of choices, and there is so much I do NOT want in this app, that I have come to prefer simpler apps  It is all what one wants. I don't begrudge the creator payment....but I do not want to pay for this. Google maps is great- this does not have it. It DOES have access to many maps- many of which one must pay for, Fair enough. But again, I can get access to the same maps (open Street Maps etc.) with other apps. I don't geo cache. Folks who do may LOVE this app. Folks who need access to a particular map, or overlay, or ability to offset, have need to use a variety of external devices, or need to convert one format to another may love this app. I have used the route editor, and found it very useful. Evidently there is a way to set up just the UI elements one needs. But it is complex......

I looked at all the major GPS apps extensively for my yearly multi-day backpacking trips. I couldn't be happier with Locus. It is dead simple to download raster maps, import and edit a kmz of the trip, add offline driving directions (which were more essential than I had expected in the back country), record the track with photos, check progress, and then export the trail and POI's to kmz to share. Everything I  was looking for and more. (OK, rendering height maps in 3D would be a nice addition some day)
Don't fool around with lesser apps. Yes, there is a learning curve, as with most things worth knowing.

I thought I had finally found the perfect navigation app. It has a great interface with a lot of powerful options. It is also the first that I know of that will bloody navigate within the app to your off road destination, and navigate you on the trail if it is marked in the map of your choice. Perfect, right?  It won't navigate offline. I'll let that sink in. You have to download a second app (BRouter) and use its nav data. That makes absolutely no sense. Locus has the maps downloaded/cached, and clearly knows how to use the GPS signal from the phone. Why in the world can't it navigate on its own offline?  Also, the free map selection for the US is just okay. This is a Euro focused app, and that is okay so long as you understand that upfront. But there are third party websites to get OpenStreetMaps downloaded straight to Locus.   All-in-all, I'll be using the app and testing it more thoroughly but the lack of offline navigation is such a serious issue that I decided to post so maybe others aren't surprised like myself.

Overall the app is nothing special but it does have some nice features that I haven't seen in other navigation apps. The most notable, at least to me, is the 'My Places' functionality. You can retrieve Google map locations in the same way you can in Google Maps. Unfortunately, the app doesn't seem to allow you to navigate to multiple points like I was hoping. It does however give you alerts when you get close to a waypoint or POI. You can add multiple waypoints along your route and get alerts when you get to a selected distance to them using the 'Guide' functionality. My goal was to create a route in Google Maps, import it into Locus, and have Locus provide audible directions to each destination I created. Not doable with this app.       Some nice features are the ability to add a custom toolbar on the right had side of the screen to access function you use a lot. You can also set the app to hide any of the 3 toolbars available automatically if you don't use them often, but it's hard to unhide them. Last but not least is the horrible documentation! I guess I should be glad there is ANY help online, but it is really basic and tells you want you probably already know.
